<Document>
<name>Furka–Grimsel–Susten Three-Pass Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Furka–Grimsel–Susten Three-Pass Loop</h2><p><i>Uri / Valais / Bern, Switzerland · Andermatt–Innertkirchen loop</i></p><p><b>Three classic Swiss passes in one day. Goldfinger filmed here; the Rhône glacier still has an ice grotto.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>78 km (48 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5 hrs no stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>June–October (Furka and Susten typically closed Nov–May)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closure dates vary by year, motorcyclists, weather changes fast, vertigo on Grimsel switchbacks</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>179</td></tr></table><hr><p>Three high passes, one perfect Alpine day. The Rhône Glacier between Furka and Grimsel feeds the river that ends in the Mediterranean — you can walk through an ice grotto carved into it each summer (which gets re-carved every June as the glacier shrinks). Goldfinger (1964) filmed the chase scene up Furka with Tilly Masterson's Mustang. Susten was built only after WWII (1938–46) specifically as a tourist drive — it follows graceful sweeps rather than the older passes' tight switchbacks. Do the loop counterclockwise (Andermatt → Furka → Grimsel → Innertkirchen → Susten → back) for the best light on the Rhône glacier.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Hotel Belvédère &amp; Rhône Glacier</b> — Iconic curved 1882 hotel on a hairpin, with the Rhône Glacier behind. An ice grotto is carved into the glacier each summer (small fee); enter the headwater of one of Europe's great rivers.</li><li><b>Furkapass summit</b> — 2,429 m. Goldfinger's 1964 chase scene was shot on the descent toward Realp. The hotel Furkablick still operates.</li><li><b>Grimsel Hospiz</b> — Modern hotel atop the dam. Alpine hospice on this pass since 1142 — pilgrims to Santiago and Rome used it. Underground tour of the Aare hydro caverns runs in summer.</li><li><b>Totensee</b> — 'Lake of the Dead' — in the 1799 Battle of Grimsel during the Napoleonic Wars, Russian and French soldiers' bodies were thrown in. Often still partly frozen in early summer.</li><li><b>Sustenpass</b> — 2,224 m. Last of the three-passes, designed expressly for cars (1938–46). Wide curves, lookouts, rest areas — feels modern compared to the older Furka and Grimsel.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
